# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-harvesting-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesters usually provide a very small amount of power for low-energy electronics.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] While the input fuel to some large-scale energy generation costs resources (oil, coal, etc.), the energy source for energy harvesters is present as ambient background.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] For example, temperature gradients exist from the operation of a combustion engine; in urban areas, there is a large amount of electromagnetic energy in the environment due to radio and television broadcasting.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One of the first examples of ambient energy being used to produce electricity was the successful use of electromagnetic radiation (EMR) to generate the crystal radio.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The principles of energy harvesting from ambient EMR can be demonstrated with basic components.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices converting ambient energy into electrical energy have attracted much interest in both the military and commercial sectors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Some systems convert motion, such as that of ocean waves, into electricity to be used by oceanographic monitoring sensors for autonomous operation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Future applications may include high-power output devices (or arrays of such devices) deployed at remote locations to serve as reliable power stations for large systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Another application is in wearable electronics, where energy-harvesting devices can power or recharge cell phones, mobile computers, and radio communication equipment.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] All of these devices must be sufficiently robust to endure long-term exposure to hostile environments and have a broad range of dynamic sensitivity to exploit the entire spectrum of wave motions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In addition, one of the latest techniques to generate electric power from vibration waves is the utilization of Auxetic Boosters.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This method falls under the category of piezoelectric-based vibration energy harvesting (PVEH), where the harvested electric energy can be directly used to power wireless sensors, monitoring cameras, and other Internet of Things (IoT) devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy can also be harvested to power small autonomous sensors such as those developed using MEMS technology.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These systems are often very small and require little power, but their applications are limited by the reliance on battery power.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Scavenging energy from ambient vibrations, wind, heat, or light could enable smart sensors to function indefinitely.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Typical power densities available from energy harvesting devices are highly dependent upon the specific application (affecting the generator's size) and the design itself of the harvesting generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In general, for motion-powered devices, typical values are a few μW/cm3 for human body-powered applications and hundreds of μW/cm3 for generators powered by machinery.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Most energy-scavenging devices for wearable electronics generate very little power.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In general, energy can be stored in a capacitor, super capacitor, or battery.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Capacitors are used when the application needs to provide huge energy spikes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Batteries leak less energy and are therefore used when the device needs to provide a steady flow of energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These aspects of the battery depend on the type that is used.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A common type of battery that is used for this purpose is the lead acid or lithium-ion battery although older types such as nickel metal hydride are still widely used today.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Compared to batteries, super capacitors have virtually unlimited charge-discharge cycles and can therefore operate forever, enabling a maintenance-free operation in IoT and wireless sensor devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Current interest in low-power energy harvesting is for independent sensor networks.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In these applications, an energy harvesting scheme puts power stored into a capacitor then boosts/regulates it to a second storage capacitor or battery for use in the microprocessor or in the data transmission.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The power is usually used in a sensor application and the data is stored or transmitted, possibly through a wireless method.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One of the main driving forces behind the search for new energy harvesting devices is the desire to power sensor networks and mobile devices without batteries that run on intermittent computing systems and need external charging or service.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Batteries have several limitations, such as limited lifespan, environmental impact, size, weight, and cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can provide an alternative or complementary source of power for applications that require low power consumption, such as remote sensing, wearable electronics, condition monitoring, and wireless sensor networks.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also extend the battery life or enable batteryless operation of some applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Another motivation for energy harvesting is the potential to address the issue of climate change by reducing greenhouse gas emissions and fossil fuel consumption.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can utilize renewable and clean sources of energy that are abundant and ubiquitous in the environment, such as solar, thermal, wind, and kinetic energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also reduce the need for power transmission and distribution systems that cause energy losses and environmental impacts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can therefore contribute to the development of a more sustainable and resilient energy system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Recent research in energy harvesting has led to the innovation of devices capable of powering themselves through user interactions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Notable examples include battery-free game boys and other toys, which showcase the potential of devices powered by the energy generated from user actions, such as pressing buttons or turning knobs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These studies highlight how energy harvested from interactions can not only power the devices themselves but also extend their operational autonomy, promoting the use of renewable energy sources and reducing reliance on traditional batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A possible source of energy comes from ubiquitous radio transmitters.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Historically, either a large collection area or close proximity to the radiating wireless energy source is needed to get useful power levels from this source.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The nantenna is one proposed development which would overcome this limitation by making use of the abundant natural radiation (such as solar radiation).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One idea is to deliberately broadcast RF energy to power and collect information from remote devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This is now commonplace in passive radio-frequency identification (RFID) systems, but the Safety and US Federal Communications Commission (and equivalent bodies worldwide) limit the maximum power that can be transmitted this way to civilian use.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This method has been used to power individual nodes in a wireless sensor network.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Various turbine and non-turbine generator technologies can harvest airflow.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Towered wind turbines and airborne wind energy systems (AWES) harness the flow of air.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Multiple companies are developing these technologies, which can operate in low-light environments, such as HVAC ducts, and can be scaled and optimized for the energy requirements of specific applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The flow of blood can also be utilized to power devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] For example, a pacemaker developed at the University of Bern, uses blood flow to wind up a spring, which then drives an electrical micro-generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Water energy harvesting has seen advancements in design, such as generators with transistor-like architecture, achieving high energy conversion efficiency and power density.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Photovoltaic (PV) energy harvesting wireless technology offers significant advantages over wired or solely battery-powered sensor solutions: virtually inexhaustible sources of power with little or no adverse environmental effects.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Indoor PV harvesting solutions have to date been powered by specially tuned amorphous silicon (aSi)a technology most used in Solar Calculators.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In recent years new PV technologies have come to the forefront in Energy Harvesting such as Dye-Sensitized Solar Cells (DSSC).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The dyes absorb light much like chlorophyll does in plants.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Electrons released on impact escape to the layer of TiO2 and from there diffuse, through the electrolyte, as the dye can be tuned to the visible spectrum much higher power can be produced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] At 200 lux a DSSC can provide over 10 μW per cm2.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into electric current or voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This strain can come from many different sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Human motion, low-frequency seismic vibrations, and acoustic noise are everyday examples.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Except in rare instances the piezoelectric effect operates in AC requiring time-varying inputs at mechanical resonance to be efficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Most piezoelectric electricity sources produce power on the order of milliwatts, too small for system application, but enough for hand-held devices such as some commercially available self-winding wristwatches.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One proposal is that they are used for micro-scale devices, such as in a device harvesting micro-hydraulic energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In this device, the flow of pressurized hydraulic fluid drives a reciprocating piston supported by three piezoelectric elements which convert the pressure fluctuations into an alternating current.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] As piezo energy harvesting has been investigated only since the late 1990s, it remains an emerging technology.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Nevertheless, some interesting improvements were made with the self-powered electronic switch at INSA school of engineering, implemented by the spin-off Arveni.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 2006, the proof of concept of a battery-less wireless doorbell push button was created, and recently, a product showed that classical wireless wallswitch can be powered by a piezo harvester.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Other industrial applications appeared between 2000 and 2005, to harvest energy from vibration and supply sensors for example, or to harvest energy from shock.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric systems can convert motion from the human body into electrical power.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] DARPA has funded efforts to harness energy from leg and arm motion, shoe impacts, and blood pressure for low level power to implantable or wearable sensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The nanobrushes are another example of a piezoelectric energy harvester.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Multiple other nanostructures have been exploited to build an energy-harvesting device, for example, a single crystal PMN-PT nanobelt was fabricated and assembled into a piezoelectric energy harvester in 2016.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Careful design is needed to minimise user discomfort.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesting sources by association affect the body.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The Vibration Energy Scavenging Project is another project that is set up to try to scavenge electrical energy from environmental vibrations and movements.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Microbelt can be used to gather electricity from respiration.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Besides, as the vibration of motion from human comes in three directions, a single piezoelectric cantilever based omni-directional energy harvester is created by using 1:2 internal resonance.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Finally, a millimeter-scale piezoelectric energy harvester has also already been created.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Piezo elements are being embedded in walkways to recover the "people energy" of footsteps.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] They can also be embedded in shoes to recover "walking energy".
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Researchers at MIT developed the first micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvester using thin film PZT in 2005.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Arman Hajati and Sang-Gook Kim invented the Ultra Wide-Bandwidth micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvesting device by exploiting the nonlinear stiffness of a doubly clamped microelectromechanical systems (MEMSs) resonator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The stretching strain in a doubly clamped beam shows a nonlinear stiffness, which provides a passive feedback and results in amplitude-stiffened Duffing mode resonance.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Typically, piezoelectric cantilevers are adopted for the above-mentioned energy harvesting system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One drawback is that the piezoelectric cantilever has gradient strain distribution, i.e., the piezoelectric transducer is not fully utilized.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] To address this issue, triangle shaped and L-shaped cantilever are proposed for uniform strain distribution.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 2018, Soochow University researchers reported hybridizing a triboelectric nanogenerator and a silicon solar cell by sharing a mutual electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This device can collect solar energy *or* convert the mechanical energy of falling raindrops into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] UK telecom company Orange UK created an energy harvesting T-shirt and boots.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Other companies have also done the same.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie gave the concept of piezoelectric effect in 1880.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into voltage or electric current and generates electric energy from motion, weight, vibration and temperature changes as shown in the figure.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Considering piezoelectric effect in thin film lead zirconate titanate $Pb(Zr,Ti)O_{3}$ PZT, microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) power generating device has been developed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] However, Aqsa further developed beam-structured electrostatic devices that are more difficult to fabricate than PZT MEMS devices versus a similar because general silicon processing involves many more mask steps that do not require PZT film.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric $d_{31}$ type sensors and actuators have a cantilever beam structure that consists of a membrane bottom electrode, film, piezoelectric film, and top electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] More than *(3~5 masks)* mask steps are required for patterning of each layer while have very low induced voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectric crystals that have a unique polar axis and have spontaneous polarization, along which the spontaneous polarization exists.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The special polar axis—crystallophysical axis *X3* – coincides with the axes *L6*,*L4*, *L3*, and *L2* of the crystals or lies in the unique straight plane *P (class "m")*.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Consequently, the electric centers of positive and negative charges are displaced of an elementary cell from equilibrium positions, i.e., the spontaneous polarization of the crystal changes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Therefore, all considered crystals have spontaneous polarization $Ps=P3$ .
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Since piezoelectric effect in pyroelectric crystals arises as a result of changes in their spontaneous polarization under external effects (electric fields, mechanical stresses).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] As a result of displacement, Aqsa Abbasi introduced change in the components $\Delta P_{s}$ along all three axes $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ .
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Suppose that $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ is proportional to the mechanical stresses causing in a first approximation, which results $\Delta P_{i}=diklTkl$ where *Tkl* represents the mechanical stress and *dikl* represents the piezoelectric modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] PZT thin films have attracted attention for applications such as force sensors, accelerometers, gyroscopes actuators, tunable optics, micro pumps, ferroelectric RAM, display systems and smart roads, when energy sources are limited, energy harvesting plays an important role in the environment.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Smart roads have the potential to play an important role in power generation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Embedding piezoelectric material in the road can convert pressure exerted by moving vehicles into voltage and current.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric sensors are most useful in smart-road technologies that can be used to create systems that are intelligent and improve productivity in the long run.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Imagine highways that alert motorists of a traffic jam before it forms.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Or bridges that report when they are at risk of collapse, or an electric grid that fixes itself when blackouts hit.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] For many decades, scientists and experts have argued that the best way to fight congestion is intelligent transportation systems, such as roadside sensors to measure traffic and synchronized traffic lights to control the flow of vehicles.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] But the spread of these technologies has been limited by cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] There are also some other smart-technology shovel ready projects which could be deployed fairly quickly, but most of the technologies are still at the development stage and might not be practically available for five years or more.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The pyroelectric effect converts a temperature change into electric current or voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] It is analogous to the piezoelectric effect, which is another type of ferroelectric behavior.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectricity requires time-varying inputs and suffers from small power outputs in energy harvesting applications due to its low operating frequencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] However, one key advantage of pyroelectrics over thermoelectrics is that many pyroelectric materials are stable up to 1200 °C or higher, enabling energy harvesting from high temperature sources and thus increasing thermodynamic efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One way to directly convert waste heat into electricity is by executing the Olsen cycle on pyroelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The Olsen cycle consists of two isothermal and two isoelectric field processes in the electric displacement-electric field (D-E) diagram.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The principle of the Olsen cycle is to charge a capacitor via cooling under low electric field and to discharge it under heating at higher electric field.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Several pyroelectric converters have been developed to implement the Olsen cycle using conduction, convection, or radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] It has also been established theoretically that pyroelectric conversion based on heat regeneration using an oscillating working fluid and the Olsen cycle can reach Carnot efficiency between a hot and a cold thermal reservoir.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Moreover, recent studies have established polyvinylidene fluoride trifluoroethylene [P(VDF-TrFE)] polymers and lead lanthanum zirconate titanate (PLZT) ceramics as promising pyroelectric materials to use in energy converters due to their large energy densities generated at low temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Additionally, a pyroelectric scavenging device that does not require time-varying inputs was recently introduced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The energy-harvesting device uses the edge-depolarizing electric field of a heated pyroelectric to convert heat energy into mechanical energy instead of drawing electric current off two plates attached to the crystal-faces.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 1821, Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a thermal gradient formed between two dissimilar conductors produces a voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] At the heart of the thermoelectric effect is the fact that a temperature gradient in a conducting material results in heat flow; this results in the diffusion of charge carriers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The flow of charge carriers between the hot and cold regions in turn creates a voltage difference.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 1834, Jean Charles Athanase Peltier discovered that running an electric current through the junction of two dissimilar conductors could, depending on the direction of the current, cause it to act as a heater or cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The heat absorbed or produced is proportional to the current, and the proportionality constant is known as the Peltier coefficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Today, due to knowledge of the Seebeck and Peltier effects, thermoelectric materials can be used as heaters, coolers and generators (TEGs).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Ideal thermoelectric materials have a high Seebeck coefficient, high electrical conductivity, and low thermal conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Low thermal conductivity is necessary to maintain a high thermal gradient at the junction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Standard thermoelectric modules manufactured today consist of P- and N-doped bismuth-telluride semiconductors sandwiched between two metallized ceramic plates.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The ceramic plates add rigidity and electrical insulation to the system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The semiconductors are connected electrically in series and thermally in parallel.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Miniature thermocouples have been developed that convert body heat into electricity and generate 40 μ W at 3 V with a 5-degree temperature gradient, while on the other end of the scale, large thermocouples are used in nuclear RTG batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Practical examples are the finger-heartratemeter by the Holst Centre and the thermogenerators by the Fraunhofer-Gesellschaft.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Thermoelectrics contain no materials that must be replenished.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One downside to thermoelectric energy conversion is low efficiency (currently less than 10%).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The development of materials that are able to operate in higher temperature gradients, and that can conduct electricity well without also conducting heat (something that was until recently thought impossible ), will result in increased efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Future work in thermoelectrics could be to convert wasted heat, such as in automobile engine combustion, into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This type of harvesting is based on the changing capacitance of vibration-dependent capacitors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Vibrations separate the plates of a charged variable capacitor, and mechanical energy is converted into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Electrostatic energy harvesters need a polarization source to work and to convert mechanical energy from vibrations into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The polarization source should be in the order of some hundreds of volts; this greatly complicates the power management circuit.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Another solution consists in using electrets, that are electrically charged dielectrics able to keep the polarization on the capacitor for years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] It's possible to adapt structures from classical electrostatic induction generators, which also extract energy from variable capacitances, for this purpose.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The resulting devices are self-biasing, and can directly charge batteries, or can produce exponentially growing voltages on storage capacitors, from which energy can be periodically extracted by DC/DC converters.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Magnetic induction refers to the production of an electromotive force (i.e., voltage) in a changing magnetic field.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This changing magnetic field can be created by motion, either rotation (i.e.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Wiegand effect and Wiegand sensors) or linear movement (i.e. vibration).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Magnets wobbling on a cantilever are sensitive to even small vibrations and generate microcurrents by moving relative to conductors due to Faraday's law of induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] By developing a miniature device of this kind in 2007, a team from the University of Southampton made possible the planting of such a device in environments that preclude having any electrical connection to the outside world.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Sensors in inaccessible places can now generate their own power and transmit data to outside receivers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One of the major limitations of the magnetic vibration energy harvester developed at University of Southampton is the size of the generator, in this case approximately one cubic centimeter, which is much too large to integrate into today's mobile technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The complete generator including circuitry is a massive 4 cm by 4 cm by 1 cm nearly the same size as some mobile devices such as the iPod nano.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Further reductions in the dimensions are possible through the integration of new and more flexible materials as the cantilever beam component.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a group at Northwestern University developed a vibration-powered generator out of polymer in the form of a spring.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This device was able to target the same frequencies as the University of Southampton groups silicon based device but with one third the size of the beam component.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A new approach to magnetic induction based energy harvesting has also been proposed by using ferrofluids.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The journal article, "Electromagnetic ferrofluid-based energy harvester", discusses the use of ferrofluids to harvest low frequency vibrational energy at 2.2 Hz with a power output of ~80 mW per g.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Quite recently, the change in domain wall pattern with the application of stress has been proposed as a method to harvest energy using magnetic induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In this study, the authors have shown that the applied stress can change the domain pattern in microwires.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Ambient vibrations can cause stress in microwires, which can induce a change in domain pattern and hence change the induction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Power, of the order of uW/cm2 has been reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Commercially successful vibration energy harvesters based on magnetic induction are still relatively few in number.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Examples include products developed by Swedish company ReVibe Energy, a technology spin-out from Saab Group.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Another example is the products developed from the early University of Southampton prototypes by Perpetuum.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These have to be sufficiently large to generate the power required by wireless sensor nodes (WSN) but in M2M applications this is not normally an issue.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These harvesters are now being supplied in large volumes to power WSNs made by companies such as GE and Emerson and also for train bearing monitoring systems made by Perpetuum.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Overhead powerline sensors can use magnetic induction to harvest energy directly from the conductor they are monitoring.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Another way of energy harvesting is through the oxidation of blood sugars.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are called biobatteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] They could be used to power implanted electronic devices (e.g., pacemakers, implanted biosensors for diabetics, implanted active RFID devices, etc.).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] At present, the Minteer Group of Saint Louis University has created enzymes that could be used to generate power from blood sugars.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] However, the enzymes would still need to be replaced after a few years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a pacemaker was powered by implantable biofuel cells at Clarkson University under the leadership of Dr.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Tree metabolic energy harvesting is a type of bio-energy harvesting.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Voltree has developed a method for harvesting energy from trees.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are being used to power remote sensors and mesh networks as the basis for a long term deployment system to monitor forest fires and weather in the forest.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] According to Voltree's website, the useful life of such a device should be limited only by the lifetime of the tree to which it is attached.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A small test network was recently deployed in a US National Park forest.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Other sources of energy from trees include capturing the physical movement of the tree in a generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Theoretical analysis of this source of energy shows some promise in powering small electronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A practical device based on this theory has been built and successfully powered a sensor node for a year.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells harvest electrical energy from the anaerobic respiration of naturally occurring soil bacteria, which provides the oxidation reaction at the anode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells can output microwatts of power, and have been used in both classroom demonstrations and to power analog radar sensors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A metamaterial-based device wirelessly converts a 900 MHz microwave signal to 7.3 volts of direct current (greater than that of a USB device).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The device can be tuned to harvest other signals including Wi-Fi signals, satellite signals, or even sound signals.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The experimental device used a series of five fiberglass and copper conductors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Conversion efficiency reached 37 percent.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] When traditional antennas are close to each other in space they interfere with each other.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] But since RF power goes down by the cube of the distance, the amount of power is very very small.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] While the claim of 7.3 volts is grand, the measurement is for an open circuit.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Since the power is so low, there can be almost no current when any load is attached.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The pressure of the atmosphere changes naturally over time from temperature changes and weather patterns.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Devices with a sealed chamber can use these pressure differences to extract energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This has been used to provide power for mechanical clocks such as the Atmos clock.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] A relatively new concept of generating energy is to generate energy from oceans.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Large masses of waters are present on the planet which carry with them great amounts of energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The energy in this case can be generated by tidal streams, ocean waves, difference in salinity and also difference in temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] As of 2018, efforts are underway to harvest energy this way.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] United States Navy recently was able to generate electricity using difference in temperatures present in the ocean.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] One method to use the temperature difference across different levels of the thermocline in the ocean is by using a thermal energy harvester that is equipped with a material that changes phase while in different temperatures regions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This is typically a polymer-based material that can handle reversible heat treatments.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] When the material is changing phase, the energy differential is converted into mechanical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The materials used will need to be able to alter phases, from liquid to solid, depending on the position of the thermocline underwater.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These phase change materials within thermal energy harvesting units would be an ideal way to recharge or power an unmanned underwater vehicle (UUV) being that it will rely on the warm and cold water already present in large bodies of water; minimizing the need for standard battery recharging.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Capturing this energy would allow for longer-term missions since the need to be collected or return for charging can be eliminated.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This is also a very environmentally friendly method of powering underwater vehicles.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] There are no emissions that come from utilizing a phase change fluid, and it will likely have a longer lifespan than that of a standard battery.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Electroactive polymers (EAPs) have been proposed for harvesting energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] These polymers have a large strain, elastic energy density, and high energy conversion efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] The total weight of systems based on EAPs (electroactive polymers) is proposed to be significantly lower than those based on piezoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Nanogenerators, such as the one made by Georgia Tech, could provide a new way for powering devices without batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] As of 2008, it only generates some dozen nanowatts, which is too low for any practical application.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Noise has been the subject of a proposal by NiPS Laboratory in Italy to harvest wide spectrum low scale vibrations via a nonlinear dynamical mechanism that can improve harvester efficiency up to a factor 4 compared to traditional linear harvesters.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Asymmetries in bistable energy harvesters can significantly affect dynamic performance and harvested power, especially under nonlinear piezoelectric coupling and parametric variability.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Recent studies show that while asymmetries may degrade response in certain regimes, they can also be exploited—through sloping angle tuning and robust parameter selection—to enhance energy conversion and outperform symmetric designs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] Combinations of different types of energy harvesters can further reduce dependence on batteries, particularly in environments where the available ambient energy types change periodically.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/energy-harvesting] This type of complementary balanced energy harvesting has the potential to increase reliability of wireless sensor systems for structural health monitoring.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A photovoltaic system employs solar modules, each comprising a number of solar cells, which generate electrical power.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV installations may be ground-mounted, rooftop-mounted, wall-mounted or floating.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The mount may be fixed or use a solar tracker to follow the sun across the sky.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic technology helps to mitigate climate change because it emits much less carbon dioxide than fossil fuels.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Other major constraints identified include competition for land use.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The use of PV as a main source requires energy storage systems or global distribution by high-voltage direct current power lines causing additional costs, and also has a number of other specific disadvantages such as variable power generation which have to be balanced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Production and installation does cause some pollution and greenhouse gas emissions, though only a fraction of the emissions caused by fossil fuels.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic systems have long been used in specialized applications as stand-alone installations and grid-connected PV systems have been in use since the 1990s.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic modules were first mass-produced in 2000, when the German government funded a one hundred thousand roof program.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Decreasing costs has allowed PV to grow as an energy source.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This has been partially driven by massive Chinese government investment in developing solar production capacity since 2000, and achieving economies of scale.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Improvements in manufacturing technology and efficiency have also led to decreasing costs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Net metering and financial incentives, such as preferential feed-in tariffs for solar-generated electricity, have supported solar PV installations in many countries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Panel prices dropped by a factor of 4 between 2004 and 2011.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Module prices dropped by about 90% over the 2010s.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2022, worldwide installed PV capacity increased to more than 1 terawatt (TW) covering nearly two percent of global electricity demand.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] After hydro and wind powers, PV is the third renewable energy source in terms of global capacity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2022, the International Energy Agency expected a growth by over 1 TW from 2022 to 2027.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In some instances, PV has offered the cheapest source of electrical power in regions with a high solar potential, with a bid for pricing as low as 0.015 US$/kWh in Qatar in 2023.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2023, the International Energy Agency stated in its World Energy Outlook that '[f]or projects with low cost financing that tap high quality resources, solar PV is now the cheapest source of electricity in history.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The term "photovoltaic" comes from the Greek φῶς (*phōs*) meaning "light", and from "volt", the unit of electromotive force, the volt, which in turn comes from the last name of the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta, inventor of the battery (electrochemical cell).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The term "photovoltaic" has been in use in English since 1849.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 1839, the French scientist Edmond Becquerel first observed the photovoltaic effect when he noted an electric current was produced by a metallic solution exposed to solar radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 1989, the German Ministry of Research and Technology initiated the first ever program to finance PV roofs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The program was led by Walter Sandtner in Bonn, Germany.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 1994, Japan followed in their footsteps and conducted a similar program with 539 residential PV systems installed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Since then, many countries have continued to produce and finance PV systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaics are best known as a method for generating electric power by using solar cells to convert energy from the sun into a flow of electrons by the photovoltaic effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar cells produce direct current electricity from sunlight which can be used to power equipment or to recharge batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The first practical application of photovoltaics was to power orbiting satellites and other spacecraft, but today the majority of photovoltaic modules are used for grid-connected systems for power generation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In this case an inverter is required to convert the DC to AC.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] There is also a smaller market for stand alone systems for remote dwellings, boats, recreational vehicles, electric cars, roadside emergency telephones, remote sensing, and cathodic protection of pipelines.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic power generation employs solar modules composed of a number of solar cells containing a semiconductor material.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Copper solar cables connect modules (module cable), arrays (array cable), and sub-fields.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Because of the growing demand for renewable energy sources, the manufacturing of solar cells and photovoltaic arrays has advanced considerably in recent years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Cells require protection from the environment and are usually packaged tightly in solar modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic module power is measured under standard test conditions (STC) in "Wp" (watts peak).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The actual power output at a particular place may be less than or greater than this rated value, depending on geographical location, time of day, weather conditions, and other factors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar photovoltaic array capacity factors are typically under 25% when not coupled with storage, which is lower than many other industrial sources of electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar-cell efficiency is the portion of energy in sunlight that is converted into electricity by a solar cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Efficiency, in combination with latitude and weather, determine the energy output of a solar system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2024, the record for solar cell efficiency was 47.6%, set in May 2022 by Fraunhofer ISE, with a III-V four-junction concentrating photovoltaic (CPV) cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The record in real-world conditions is held by NREL, which developed triple junction cells with a tested efficiency of 39.5%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Commercial solar modules may exceed 24% efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2025, the best reached 24.5%, typically lower than their cells in isolation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The most efficient mass-produced solar modules have power density values of 175 W/m2 (16.22 W/ft2).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2026 using triple III-V germanium cells and shingled matrix technology to interconnect cells, Fraunhofer achieved efficiency of 34.4%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] An important innovation was the use of direct cell-to-cell contact, eliminating traditional solder-coated copper ribbons and the resulting shading of active cell areas.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Several factors affect conversion efficiency, including its reflectance, thermodynamic efficiency, charge carrier separation efficiency, charge carrier collection efficiency and conduction efficiency values.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Because these parameters are difficult to directly measure, other parameters are measured instead, including quantum efficiency, open-circuit voltage (VOC) ratio, and § Fill factor.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Reflectance losses are accounted for by the quantum efficiency value, as they affect external quantum efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Recombination losses are accounted for by these factors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Resistive losses are predominantly accounted for by the fill factor value, but also contribute to the others.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Depending on construction, photovoltaic modules can produce electricity from a range of frequencies of light, but usually cannot cover the entire solar radiation range (specifically, ultraviolet, visible, infrared and low or diffused light).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Hence, much of the incident sunlight energy is not processed by solar modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Sunlight can be split into wavelength bands (each a different color), each directed onto cells tuned to those ranges that can convert that band more efficiently.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Module performance is generally rated under standard test conditions (STC): irradiance of 1,000 W/m2, solar spectrum of AM 1.5 and module temperature at 25 °C.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The actual voltage and current output of the module changes as lighting, temperature and load conditions change, so there is never one specific voltage at which the module operates.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Performance varies depending on geographic location, time of day, the day of the year, amount of solar irradiance, direction and tilt of modules, cloud cover, shading, soiling, state of charge, and temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Performance of a module or panel can be measured at different time intervals with a DC clamp meter or shunt and logged, graphed, or charted with a chart recorder or data logger.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] For optimum performance, a solar panel needs to be made of similar modules oriented in the same direction perpendicular to direct sunlight.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Bypass diodes are used to circumvent broken or shaded panels and optimize output.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] These bypass diodes are usually placed along groups of solar cells to create a continuous flow.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Electrical characteristics include nominal power (PMAX, measured in W), open-circuit voltage (VOC), short-circuit current (ISC, measured in amperes), maximum power voltage (VMPP), maximum power current (IMPP), peak power (watt-peak, Wp), and module efficiency (%).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Open-circuit voltage or VOC is the maximum voltage the module can produce when not connected to an electrical circuit or system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] VOC can be measured with a voltmeter directly on an illuminated module's terminals or on its disconnected cable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The peak power rating, Wp, is the maximum output under standard test conditions (not the maximum possible output).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Typical modules, which could measure approximately 1 by 2 metres (3 ft × 7 ft), will be rated from as low as 75 W to as high as 600 W, depending on their efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] At the time of testing, the test modules are binned according to their test results, and a typical manufacturer might rate their modules in 5 W increments, and either rate them at +/- 3%, +/-5%, +3/-0% or +5/-0%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The performance of a photovoltaic (PV) module depends on the environmental conditions, mainly on the global incident irradiance G in the plane of the module.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] However, the temperature T of the p–n junction also influences the main electrical parameters: the short circuit current ISC, the open circuit voltage VOC and the maximum power Pmax.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In general, it is known that VOC shows a significant inverse correlation with T, while for ISC this correlation is direct, but weaker, so that this increase does not compensate for the decrease in VOC.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As a consequence, Pmax decreases when T increases.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Temperature sensitivity is usually described by temperature coefficients, each of which expresses the derivative of the parameter to which it refers with respect to the junction temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Techniques for estimating these coefficients from experimental data can be found in the literature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The ability of solar modules to withstand damage by rain, hail, heavy snow load, and cycles of heat and cold varies by manufacturer, although most solar panels on the U.S. market are UL listed, meaning they have gone through testing to withstand hail.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Potential-induced degradation (also called PID) is a potential-induced performance degradation in crystalline photovoltaic modules, caused by so-called stray currents.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This effect may cause power loss of up to 30%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The largest challenge for photovoltaic technology is the purchase price per watt of electricity produced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Advancements in photovoltaic technologies have brought about the process of "doping" the silicon substrate to lower the activation energy thereby making the panel more efficient in converting photons to retrievable electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Chemicals such as boron (p-type) are applied into the semiconductor crystal in order to create donor and acceptor energy levels substantially closer to the valence and conductor bands.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In doing so, the addition of boron impurity allows the activation energy to decrease twenty-fold from 1.12 eV to 0.05 eV.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Since the potential difference (EB) is so low, the boron is able to thermally ionize at room temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This allows for free energy carriers in the conduction and valence bands thereby allowing greater conversion of photons to electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The power output of a photovoltaic (PV) device decreases over time.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This decrease is due to its exposure to solar radiation as well as other external conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The degradation index, which is defined as the annual percentage of output power loss, is a key factor in determining the long-term production of a photovoltaic plant.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] To estimate this degradation, the percentage of decrease associated with each of the electrical parameters.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The individual degradation of a photovoltaic module can significantly influence the performance of a complete string.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Furthermore, not all modules in the same installation decrease their performance at exactly the same rate.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Given a set of modules exposed to long-term outdoor conditions, the individual degradation of the main electrical parameters and the increase in their dispersion must be considered.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As each module tends to degrade differently, the behavior of the modules will be increasingly different over time, negatively affecting the overall performance of the plant.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] There are several studies dealing with the power degradation analysis of modules based on different photovoltaic technologies available in the literature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] According to a recent study, the degradation of crystalline silicon modules is very regular, oscillating between 0.8% and 1.0% per year.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Strong seasonal variations are also observed in such thin-film technologies because the influence of the solar spectrum is much greater.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] For example, for modules of amorphous silicon, micromorphic silicon or cadmium telluride, we are talking about annual degradation rates for the first years of between 3% and 4%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] However, other technologies, such as CIGS, show much lower degradation rates, even in those early years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Overall the manufacturing process of creating solar photovoltaics is simple in that it does not require the culmination of many complex or moving parts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Because of the solid-state nature of PV systems, they often have relatively long lifetimes, anywhere from 10 to 30 years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] To increase the electrical output of a PV system, the manufacturer must simply add more photovoltaic components.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Because of this, economies of scale are important for manufacturers as costs decrease with increasing output.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] While there are many types of PV systems known to be effective, crystalline silicon PV accounted for around 90% of the worldwide production of PV in 2013.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Manufacturing silicon PV systems has several steps.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] First, polysilicon is processed from mined quartz until it is very pure (semi-conductor grade).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This is melted down with small amounts of boron, a group III element, to make a p-type semiconductor rich in electron holes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Typically using a seed crystal, an ingot of this solution is grown from the liquid polycrystalline.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Wafers of this semiconductor material are cut from the bulk material with wire saws, and then go through surface etching before being cleaned.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Next, the wafers are placed into a phosphorus vapor deposition furnace which lays a very thin layer of phosphorus, a group V element, which creates an n-type semiconducting surface.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] To reduce energy losses, an anti-reflective coating is added to the surface, along with electrical contacts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] After finishing the cell, cells are connected via electrical circuit according to the specific application and prepared for shipping and installation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Data required to investigate their impact are sometimes affected by a rather large amount of uncertainty.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The values of human labor and water consumption, for example, are not precisely assessed due to the lack of systematic and accurate analyses in the scientific literature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] One difficulty in determining effects due to PV is to determine if the wastes are released to the air, water, or soil during the manufacturing phase.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Life-cycle assessments, which look at all different environment effects ranging from global warming potential, pollution, water depletion and others, are unavailable for PV.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Thus, estimates of the environmental impact of PV have focused on carbon dioxide equivalents per kWh or energy pay-back time (EPBT).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT describes the timespan a PV system needs to operate in order to generate the same amount of energy that was used for its manufacture.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Another study includes transport energy costs in the EPBT.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT has also been defined completely differently as "the time needed to compensate for the total renewable- and non-renewable primary energy required during the life cycle of a PV system" in another study, which also included installation costs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This energy amortization, given in years, is also referred to as *break-even* energy payback time.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The lower the EPBT, the lower the environmental cost of solar power.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT depends vastly on the location where the PV system is installed (e.g. the amount of sunlight available and the efficiency of the electrical grid) and on the type of system, namely the system's components.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A 2015 review of EPBT estimates of first and second-generation PV suggested that there was greater variation in embedded energy than in efficiency of the cells implying that it was mainly the embedded energy that needs to reduce to have a greater reduction in EPBT.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In general, the most important component of solar panels, which accounts for much of the energy use and greenhouse gas emissions, is the refining of the polysilicon.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As to how much percentage of the EPBT this silicon depends on the type of system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT relates closely to the concepts of net energy gain (NEG) and energy returned on energy invested (EROI).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] They are both used in energy economics and refer to the difference between the energy expended to harvest an energy source and the amount of energy gained from that harvest.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The NEG and EROI also take the operating lifetime of a PV system into account and a working life of 25 to 30 years is typically assumed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] From these metrics, the Energy payback Time can be derived by calculation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV systems using crystalline silicon, by far the majority of the systems in practical use, have such a high EPBT because silicon is produced by the reduction of high-grade quartz sand in electric furnaces.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This coke-fired smelting process occurs at high temperatures of more than 1000 °C and is very energy intensive, using about 11 kilowatt-hours (kWh) per produced kilogram of silicon.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The energy requirements of this process makes the energy cost per unit of silicon produced relatively inelastic, which means that the production process itself will not become more efficient in the future.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Nonetheless, the energy payback time has shortened significantly over the last years, as crystalline silicon cells became ever more efficient in converting sunlight, while the thickness of the wafer material was constantly reduced and therefore required less silicon for its manufacture.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Within the last ten years, the amount of silicon used for solar cells declined from 16 to 6 grams per watt-peak.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In the same period, the thickness of a c-Si wafer was reduced from 300 μm, or microns, to about 160–190 μm.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The sawing techniques that slice crystalline silicon ingots into wafers have also improved by reducing the kerf loss and making it easier to recycle the silicon sawdust.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Crystalline silicon modules are the most extensively studied PV type in terms of LCA since they are the most commonly used.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Mono-crystalline silicon photovoltaic systems (mono-si) have an average efficiency of 14.0%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The cells tend to follow a structure of front electrode, anti-reflection film, n-layer, p-layer, and back electrode, with the sun hitting the front electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The cradle to gate of CO2-eq/kWh ranges from 37.3 to 72.2 grams when installed in Southern Europe.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Techniques to produce multi-crystalline silicon (multi-si) photovoltaic cells are simpler and cheaper than mono-si, however tend to make less efficient cells, an average of 13.2%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The cradle to gate of CO2-eq/kWh ranges from 28.5 to 69 grams when installed in Southern Europe.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Outside of Europe, where net grid efficiencies are lower, it would take longer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This 'energy payback time' can be seen as the portion of time during the useful lifetime of the module in which the energy production is polluting.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] At best, this means that a 30-year old panel has produced clean energy for 97% of its lifetime, or that the silicon in the modules in a solar panel produce 97% less greenhouse gas emissions than a coal-fired plant for the same amount of energy (assuming and ignoring many things).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Some studies have looked beyond EPBT and GWP to other environmental effects.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In one such study, conventional energy mix in Greece was compared to multi-si PV and found a 95% overall reduction in effects including carcinogens, eco-toxicity, acidification, eutrophication, and eleven others.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Cadmium telluride (CdTe) is one of the fastest-growing thin film based solar cells which are collectively known as second-generation devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This new thin-film device also shares similar performance restrictions (Shockley-Queisser efficiency limit) as conventional Si devices but promises to lower the cost of each device by both reducing material and energy consumption during manufacturing.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The global market share of CdTe was 4.7% in 2008.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This technology's highest power conversion efficiency is 21%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The cell structure includes glass substrate (around 2 mm), transparent conductor layer, CdS buffer layer (50–150 nm), CdTe absorber and a metal contact layer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] CdTe PV systems require less energy input in their production than other commercial PV systems per unit electricity production.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The average CO2-eq/kWh is around 18 grams (cradle to gate).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] CdTe has the fastest EPBT of all commercial PV technologies, which varies between 0.3 and 1.2 years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Third-generation PVs are designed to combine the advantages of both the first and second generation devices and they do not have Shockley-Queisser limit, a theoretical limit for first and second generation PV cells.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The thickness of a third generation device is less than 1 μm.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Two new promising thin film technologies are copper zinc tin sulfide (Cu2ZnSnS4 or CZTS), zinc phosphide (Zn3P2) and single-walled carbon nano-tubes (SWCNT).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] These thin films are currently only produced in the lab but may be commercialized in the future.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The manufacturing of CZTS and (Zn3P2) processes are expected to be similar to those of current thin film technologies of CIGS and CdTe, respectively.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] While CZTS and Zn3P2 offer good promise for these reasons, the specific environmental implications of their commercial production are not yet known.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Global warming potential of CZTS and Zn3P2 were found 38 and 30 grams CO2-eq/kWh while their corresponding EPBT were found 1.85 and 0.78 years, respectively.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Overall, CdTe and Zn3P2 have similar environmental effects but can slightly outperform CIGS and CZTS.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A study on environmental impacts of SWCNT PVs by Celik et al., including an existing 1% efficient device and a theoretical 28% efficient device, found that, compared to monocrystalline Si, the environmental impacts from 1% SWCNT was ~18 times higher due mainly to the short lifetime of three years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] There have been major changes in the underlying costs, industry structure and market prices of solar photovoltaics technology, over the years, and gaining a coherent picture of the shifts occurring across the industry value chain globally is a challenge.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Further complexities result from the many different policy support initiatives that have been put in place to facilitate photovoltaics commercialisation in various countries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Renewable energy technologies have generally gotten cheaper since their invention.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Renewable energy systems have become cheaper to build than fossil fuel power plants across much of the world, thanks to advances in wind and solar energy technology, in particular.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] There is no silver bullet in electricity or energy demand and bill management, because customers (sites) have different specific situations, e.g. different comfort/convenience needs, different electricity tariffs, or different usage patterns.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Electricity tariff may have a few elements, such as daily access and metering charge, energy charge (based on kWh, MWh) or peak demand charge (e.g. a price for the highest 30min energy consumption in a month).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV is a promising option for reducing energy charges when electricity prices are reasonably high and continuously increasing, such as in Australia and Germany.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] However, for sites with peak demand charge in place, PV may be less attractive if peak demands mostly occur in the late afternoon to early evening, for example in residential communities.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Overall, energy investment is largely an economic decision and it is better to make investment decisions based on systematic evaluation of options in operational improvement, energy efficiency, onsite generation and energy storage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 1977 crystalline silicon solar cell prices were at $76.67/W.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Manufacturers were able to maintain a positive operating margin despite a 50% drop in income due to innovation and reductions in costs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In late 2011, factory-gate prices for crystalline-silicon photovoltaic modules suddenly dropped below the $1.00/W mark, taking many in the industry by surprise, and has caused a number of solar manufacturing companies to go bankrupt throughout the world.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The $1.00/W cost is often regarded in the PV industry as marking the achievement of grid parity for PV, but most experts do not believe this price point is sustainable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Technological advancements, manufacturing process improvements, and industry re-structuring, may mean that further price reductions are possible.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The average retail price of solar cells as monitored by the Solarbuzz group fell from $3.50/watt to $2.43/watt over the course of 2011.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2013 wholesale prices had fallen to $0.74/W.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This has been cited as evidence supporting 'Swanson's law', an observation similar to the famous Moore's Law, which claims that solar cell prices fall 20% for every doubling of industry capacity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The Fraunhofer Institute defines the 'learning rate' as the drop in prices as the cumulative production doubles, some 25% between 1980 and 2010.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Although the prices for modules have dropped quickly, current inverter prices have dropped at a much lower rate, and in 2019 constitute over 61% of the cost per kWp, from a quarter in the early 2000s.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Note that the prices mentioned above are for bare modules, another way of looking at module prices is to include installation costs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In the US, according to the Solar Energy Industries Association, the price of installed rooftop PV modules for homeowners fell from $9.00/W in 2006 to $5.46/W in 2011.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Including the prices paid by industrial installations, the national installed price drops to $3.45/W.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This is markedly higher than elsewhere in the world, in Germany homeowner rooftop installations averaged at $2.24/W.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The cost differences are thought to be primarily based on the higher regulatory burden and lack of a national solar policy in the US.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] By the end of 2012 Chinese manufacturers had production costs of $0.50/W in the cheapest modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In some markets distributors of these modules can earn a considerable margin, buying at factory-gate price and selling at the highest price the market can support ('value-based pricing').
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In California PV reached grid parity in 2011, which is usually defined as PV production costs at or below retail electricity prices (though often still above the power station prices for coal or gas-fired generation without their distribution and other costs).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity had been reached in 19 markets in 2014.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] By 2024, massive increases of production of solar panels in China had caused module prices to drop to as low as $0.11/W, an over 90 percent reduction from 2011 prices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The levelised cost of electricity (LCOE) is the cost per kWh based on the costs distributed over the project lifetime, and is thought to be a better metric for calculating viability than price per wattage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] LCOEs vary dramatically depending on the location.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The LCOE can be considered the minimum price customers will have to pay the utility company in order for it to break even on the investment in a new power station.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity is roughly achieved when the LCOE falls to a similar price as conventional local grid prices, although in actuality the calculations are not directly comparable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Large industrial PV installations had reached grid parity in California in 2011.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity for rooftop systems was still believed to be much farther away at this time.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Many LCOE calculations are not thought to be accurate, and a large amount of assumptions are required.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Module prices may drop further, and the LCOE for solar may correspondingly drop in the future.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] These costs are not factored into LCOE calculations, nor are special subsidies or premiums that may make buying solar power more attractive.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The unreliability and temporal variation in generation of solar and wind power is a major problem.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Too much of these volatile power sources can cause instability of the entire grid.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2017 power-purchase agreement prices for solar farms below $0.05/kWh are common in the United States, and the lowest bids in some Persian Gulf countries were about $0.03/kWh.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The goal of the United States Department of Energy is to achieve a levelised cost of energy for solar PV of $0.03/kWh for utility companies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Financial incentives for photovoltaics, such as feed-in tariffs (FITs), were often offered to electricity consumers to install and operate solar-electric generating systems, and in some countries such subsidies are the only way photovoltaics can remain economically profitable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV FITs were crucial for early growth of photovoltaics.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Germany and Spain were the most important countries offering subsidies for PV, and the policies of these countries drove demand.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Some US solar cell manufacturing companies have repeatedly complained that the dropping prices of PV module costs have been achieved due to subsidies by the government of China, and the dumping of these products below fair market prices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] US manufacturers generally recommend high tariffs on foreign supplies to allow them remain profitable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In response to these concerns, the Obama administration began to levy tariffs on US consumers of these products in 2012 to raise prices for domestic manufacturers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The USA, however, also subsidies the industry.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Some environmentalists have promoted the idea that government incentives should be used in order to expand the PV manufacturing industry to reduce costs of PV-generated electricity much more rapidly to a level where it is able to compete with fossil fuels in a free market.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This is based on the theory that when the manufacturing capacity doubles, economies of scale will cause the prices of the solar products to halve.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In many countries access to capital is lacking to develop PV projects.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] To solve this problem, securitization is sometimes used to accelerate development of solar photovoltaic projects.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic power is also generated during a time of day that is close to peak demand (precedes it) in electricity systems with high use of air conditioning.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Since large-scale PV operation requires back-up in the form of spinning reserves, its marginal cost of generation in the middle of the day is typically lowest, but not zero, when PV is generating electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This can be seen in Figure 1 of this paper:.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] For residential properties with private PV facilities networked to the grid, the owner may be able earn extra money when the time of generation is included, as electricity is worth more during the day than at night.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] One journalist theorised in 2012 that if the energy bills of Americans were forced upwards by imposing an extra tax of $50/ton on carbon dioxide emissions from coal-fired power, this could have allowed solar PV to appear more cost-competitive to consumers in most locations.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar and wind power are scaling up faster than previous sources of electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Declining costs, modular design, and improved battery storage help the transition to renewable energy, especially for solar.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar photovoltaics formed the largest body of research among the seven sustainable energy types examined in a global bibliometric study, with the annual scientific output growing from 9,094 publications in 2011 to 14,447 publications in 2019.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Likewise, the application of solar photovoltaics is growing rapidly and the worldwide installed capacity reached one terawatt in April 2022.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The total power output of the world's PV capacity in a calendar year is now beyond 500 TWh of electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] This represents 2% of worldwide electricity demand.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] More than 100 countries, such as Brazil and India, use solar PV.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] China is followed by the United States and Japan, while installations in Germany, once the world's largest producer, have been slowing down.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Honduras generated the highest percentage of its energy from solar in 2019, 14.8%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2019, Vietnam has the highest installed capacity in Southeast Asia, about 4.5 GW.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The annualized installation rate of about 90 W per capita per annum places Vietnam among world leaders.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Generous Feed-in tariff (FIT) and government supporting policies such as tax exemptions were the key to enable Vietnam's solar PV boom.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Underlying drivers include the government's desire to enhance energy self-sufficiency and the public's demand for local environmental quality.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A key barrier is limited transmission grid capacity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] China has the world's largest solar power capacity, with 1048 GW of installed capacity in 2024 compared with about 339 GW in the European Union, according to International Energy Agency data.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Other countries with the world's largest solar power capacities include the United States, Japan and Germany.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] In 2017, it was thought probable that by 2030 global PV installed capacities could be between 3,000 and 10,000 GW.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Greenpeace in 2010 claimed that 1,845 GW of PV systems worldwide could be generating approximately 2,646 TWh/year of electricity by 2030, and by 2050 over 20% of all electricity could be provided by PV.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] There are many practical applications for the use of solar panels or photovoltaics covering every technological domain under the sun.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] From the fields of the agricultural industry as a power source for irrigation to its usage in remote health care facilities to refrigerate medical supplies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Other applications include power generation at various scales and attempts to integrate them into homes and public infrastructure.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV modules are used in photovoltaic systems and include a large variety of electrical devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A photovoltaic system, or solar PV system is a power system designed to supply usable solar power by means of photovoltaics.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] It consists of an arrangement of several components, including solar panels to absorb and directly convert sunlight into electricity, a solar inverter to change the electric current from DC to AC, as well as mounting, cabling and other electrical accessories.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] PV systems range from small, roof-top mounted or building-integrated systems with capacities from a few to several tens of kilowatts, to large utility-scale power stations of hundreds of megawatts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Nowadays, most PV systems are grid-connected, while stand-alone systems only account for a small portion of the market.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photosensors are sensors of light or other electromagnetic radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] A photo detector has a p–n junction that converts light photons into current.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] The absorbed photons make electron–hole pairs in the depletion region.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Photodiodes and photo transistors are a few examples of photo detectors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p01] Solar cells convert some of the light energy absorbed into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Crystalline silicon photovoltaics are only one type of PV, and while they represent the majority of solar cells produced currently there are many new and promising technologies that have the potential to be scaled up to meet future energy needs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] As of 2018, crystalline silicon cell technology serves as the basis for several PV module types, including monocrystalline, multicrystalline, mono PERC, and bifacial.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Another newer technology, thin-film PV, are manufactured by depositing semiconducting layers of perovskite, a mineral with semiconductor properties, on a substrate in vacuum.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The substrate is often glass or stainless-steel, and these semiconducting layers are made of many types of materials including cadmium telluride (CdTe), copper indium diselenide (CIS), copper indium gallium diselenide (CIGS), and amorphous silicon (a-Si).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] After being deposited onto the substrate the semiconducting layers are separated and connected by electrical circuit by laser scribing.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite solar cells are a very efficient solar energy converter and have excellent optoelectronic properties for photovoltaic purposes, but their upscaling from lab-sized cells to large-area modules is still under research.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Thin-film photovoltaic materials may possibly become attractive in the future, because of the reduced materials requirements and cost to manufacture modules consisting of thin-films as compared to silicon-based wafers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In 2019 university labs at Oxford, Stanford and elsewhere reported perovskite solar cells with efficiencies of 20-25%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Copper indium gallium selenide (CIGS) is a thin film solar cell based on the copper indium diselenide (CIS) family of chalcopyrite semiconductors.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] CIS and CIGS are often used interchangeably within the CIS/CIGS community.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The cell structure includes soda lime glass as the substrate, Mo layer as the back contact, CIS/CIGS as the absorber layer, cadmium sulfide (CdS) or Zn (S,OH)x as the buffer layer, and ZnO:Al as the front contact.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] CIGS is approximately 1/100 the thickness of conventional silicon solar cell technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Materials necessary for assembly are readily available, and are less costly per watt of solar cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] CIGS based solar devices resist performance degradation over time and are highly stable in the field.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Reported global warming potential impacts of CIGS ranges 20.5–58.8 grams CO2-eq/kWh of electricity generated for different solar irradiation (1,700 to 2,200 kWh/m2/y) and power conversion efficiency (7.8 – 9.12%).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] EPBT ranges from 0.2 to 1.4 years, while harmonized value of EPBT was found 1.393 years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Toxicity is an issue within the buffer layer of CIGS modules because it contains cadmium and gallium.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] CIS modules do not contain any heavy metals.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] A perovskite solar cell (PSC) is a type of solar cell that includes a perovskite-structured compound, most commonly a hybrid organic–inorganic lead or tin halide-based material as the light-harvesting active layer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite materials, such as methylammonium lead halides the all-inorganic cesium lead halide, are cheap to produce and simple to manufacture.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Solar-cell efficiencies of laboratory-scale devices using these materials have increased from 3.8% in 2009 to 27% in 2025 in single-junction architectures, and, in silicon-based tandem cells, to 34.85%, exceeding the maximum efficiency achieved in single-junction silicon solar cells.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite solar cells have therefore been the fastest-advancing solar technology as of 2016.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] With the potential of achieving even higher efficiencies and very low production costs, perovskite solar cells have become commercially attractive.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Core problems and research subjects include their long-term stability, high sensitivity to moisture, and toxicity if lead is used.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Managing toxic lead in PSCs is essential, as exposure presents significant health risks, including neurological disorders.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Because PSCs are an emerging technology, lead toxicity remains a major hurdle to widespread adoption and commercialization.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Dye-sensitized solar cells (DSCs) are a novel thin film solar cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] These solar cells operate under ambient light better than other photovoltaic technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] They work with light being absorbed in a sensitizing dye between two charge transport materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Dye surrounds TiO2 nanoparticles which are in a sintered network.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] TiO2 acts as conduction band in an n-type semiconductor; the scaffold for adorned dye molecules and transports elections during excitation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] For TiO2 DSC technology, sample preparation at high temperatures is very effective because higher temperatures produce more suitable textural properties.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Another example of DSCs is the copper complex with Cu (II/I) as a redox shuttle with TMBY (4,4',6,6'-tetramethyl-2,2'bipyridine).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] DSCs show great performance with artificial and indoor light.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] From a range of 200 lux to 2,000 lux, these cells operate at conditions of a maximum efficiency of 29.7%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] However, there have been issues with DSCs, many of which come from the liquid electrolyte.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The solvent is hazardous, and will permeate most plastics.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Because it is liquid, it is unstable to temperature variation, leading to freezing in cold temperatures and expansion in warm temperatures causing failure.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Another disadvantage is that the solar cell is not ideal for large scale application because of its low efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Some of the benefits for DSC is that it can be used in a variety of light levels (including cloudy conditions), it has a low production cost, and it does not degrade under sunlight, giving it a longer lifetime then other types of thin film solar cells.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Other possible future PV technologies include organic, dye-sensitized and quantum-dot photovoltaics.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Organic photovoltaics (OPVs) fall into the thin-film category of manufacturing, and typically operate around the 12% efficiency range which is lower than the 12–21% typically seen by silicon-based PVs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Because organic photovoltaics require very high purity and are relatively reactive they must be encapsulated which vastly increases the cost of manufacturing and means that they are not feasible for large scale-up.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Dye-sensitized PVs are similar in efficiency to OPVs but are significantly easier to manufacture.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] However, these dye-sensitized photovoltaics present storage problems because the liquid electrolyte is toxic and can potentially permeate the plastics used in the cell.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Quantum dot solar cells are solution-processed, meaning they are potentially scalable, but currently they peak at 12% efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Organic and polymer photovoltaic (OPV) are a relatively new area of research.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The tradition OPV cell structure layers consist of a semi-transparent electrode, electron blocking layer, tunnel junction, holes blocking layer, electrode, with the sun hitting the transparent electrode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] OPV replaces silver with carbon as an electrode material lowering manufacturing cost and making them more environmentally friendly.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] OPV are flexible, low weight, and work well with roll-to roll manufacturing for mass production.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] OPV uses "only abundant elements coupled to an extremely low embodied energy through very low processing temperatures using only ambient processing conditions on simple printing equipment enabling energy pay-back times".
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Current efficiencies range 1–6.5%, however theoretical analyses show promise beyond 10% efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Many different configurations of OPV exist using different materials for each layer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] OPV technology rivals existing PV technologies in terms of EPBT even if they currently present a shorter operational lifetime.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] A 2013 study analyzed 12 different configurations all with 2% efficiency, the EPBT ranged from 0.29 to 0.52 years for 1 m2 of PV.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The average CO2-eq/kWh for OPV is 54.922 grams.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Thermophotovoltaic (TPV) energy conversion is a direct conversion process from heat to electricity via photons.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] A basic thermophotovoltaic system consists of a hot object emitting thermal radiation and a photovoltaic cell similar to a solar cell but tuned to the spectrum being emitted from the hot object.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] As TPV systems generally work at lower temperatures than solar cells, their efficiencies tend to be low.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Offsetting this through the use of multi-junction cells based on non-silicon materials is common, but generally very expensive.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] This currently limits TPV to niche roles like spacecraft power and waste heat collection from larger systems like steam turbines.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Photovoltaic-Thermoelectric Generator (PV-TEG) hybrid system is a type of hybrid PV cell that pairs a photovoltaic (PV) cell with a thermoelectric generator (TEG).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] TEGs rely on the Seebeck effect, a phenomenon that occurs when a junction of two conducting materials experience a temperature difference thereby, inducing an electromotive force.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The resulting voltage is directly proportional to the temperature difference.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] During the process of converting light into electricity, heat dissipates, making PV cells less efficient at high temperatures and reducing their lifespan.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] By integrating a TEG into the system, heat is facilitated away from the PV cell and converts it into electricity, thereby improving its efficiency and longevity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The thermoelectric figure of merit ZT, determines the efficiency of converting heat into electricity as well as the ability to cool.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Optimizing parameters such as electrical conductivity (σ), Seebeck coefficient (S), thermal conductivity (κ) are of interest to maximize efficiencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Common thermoelectric materials typically have a ZT value of about 1, corresponding to an efficiency of approximately 10% or less.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] While typical TEGs have a low conversion efficiency, ongoing research in thermoelectric materials such as BiTe (ZT = 2.4) , SnSe (ZT = 2.6), and half-Heusler compounds (ZT = 1.6) have led to improvement in efficiency over the years.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Theoretical predictions indicate greater potential for optimization, with estimated values of 14 for BiTe, 2.6 for SnSe, and 2.2 for half-Heusler.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] A number of solar modules may also be mounted vertically above each other in a tower, if the zenith distance of the Sun is greater than zero, and the tower can be turned horizontally as a whole and each module additionally around a horizontal axis.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In such a tower the modules can follow the Sun exactly.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Such a device may be described as a ladder mounted on a turnable disk.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Each step of that ladder is the middle axis of a rectangular solar panel.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In case the zenith distance of the Sun reaches zero, the "ladder" may be rotated to the north or the south to avoid a solar module producing a shadow on a lower one.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Instead of an exactly vertical tower one can choose a tower with an axis directed to the polar star, meaning that it is parallel to the rotation axis of the Earth.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In this case the angle between the axis and the Sun is always larger than 66 degrees.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] During a day it is only necessary to turn the panels around this axis to follow the Sun.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Installations may be ground-mounted (and sometimes integrated with farming and grazing) or built into the roof or walls of a building (building-integrated photovoltaics).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Where land may be limited, PV can be deployed as floating solar.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In 2008 the Far Niente Winery pioneered the world's first "floatovoltaic" system by installing 994 photovoltaic solar panels onto 130 pontoons and floating them on the winery's irrigation pond.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] A benefit of the set up is that the panels are kept at a lower temperature than they would be on land, leading to a higher efficiency of solar energy conversion.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The floating panels also reduce the amount of water lost through evaporation and inhibit the growth of algae.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Concentrator photovoltaics is a technology that contrary to conventional flat-plate PV systems uses lenses and curved mirrors to focus sunlight onto small, but highly efficient, multi-junction solar cells.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] These systems sometimes use solar trackers and a cooling system to increase their efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In 2019, the world record for solar cell efficiency at 47.1% was achieved by using multi-junction concentrator solar cells, developed at National Renewable Energy Laboratory, Colorado, US.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The highest efficiencies achieved without concentration include a material by Sharp Corporation at 35.8% using a proprietary triple-junction manufacturing technology in 2009, and Boeing Spectrolab (40.7% also using a triple-layer design).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] There is an ongoing effort to increase the conversion efficiency of PV cells and modules, primarily for competitive advantage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In order to increase the efficiency of solar cells, it is important to choose a semiconductor material with an appropriate band gap that matches the solar spectrum.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] This will enhance the electrical and optical properties.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Improving the method of charge collection is also useful for increasing the efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] There are several groups of materials that are being developed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Ultrahigh-efficiency devices (η>30%) are made by using GaAs and GaInP2 semiconductors with multijunction tandem cells.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] High-quality, single-crystal silicon materials are used to achieve high-efficiency, low cost cells (η>20%).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Recent developments in organic photovoltaic cells (OPVs) have made significant advancements in power conversion efficiency from 3% to over 15% since their introduction in the 1980s.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] To date, the highest reported power conversion efficiency ranges 6.7–8.94% for small molecule, 8.4–10.6% for polymer OPVs, and 7–21% for perovskite OPVs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] OPVs are expected to play a major role in the PV market.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Recent improvements have increased the efficiency and lowered cost, while remaining environmentally-benign and renewable.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Several companies have begun embedding power optimizers into PV modules called smart modules.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] These modules perform maximum power point tracking (MPPT) for each module individually, measure performance data for monitoring, and provide additional safety features.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Such modules can also compensate for shading effects, wherein a shadow falling across a section of a module causes the electrical output of one or more strings of cells in the module to decrease.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] One of the major causes for the decreased performance of cells is overheating.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The efficiency of a solar cell declines by about 0.5% for every 1 degree Celsius increase in temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] This means that a 100 degree increase in surface temperature could decrease the efficiency of a solar cell by about half.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Self-cooling solar cells are one solution to this problem.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Rather than using energy to cool the surface, pyramid and cone shapes can be formed from silica, and attached to the surface of a solar panel.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Doing so allows visible light to reach the solar cells, but reflects infrared rays (which carry heat).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The 122 PW of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface is plentiful—almost 10,000 times more than the 13 TW equivalent of average power consumed in 2005 by humans.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] This abundance leads to the suggestion that it will not be long before solar energy will become the world's primary energy source.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Additionally, solar radiation has the highest power density (global mean of 170 W/m2) among renewable energies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Solar power is pollution-free during use, which enables it to cut down on pollution when it is substituted for other energy sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] For example, MIT estimated that 52,000 people per year die prematurely in the U.S. from coal-fired power plant pollution and all but one of these deaths could be prevented from using PV to replace coal.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Production end-wastes and emissions are manageable using existing pollution controls.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] End-of-use recycling technologies are under development and policies are being produced that encourage recycling from producers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Solar panels are usually guaranteed for 25 years (but inverters tend to fail sooner), with little maintenance or intervention after their initial set-up, so after the initial capital cost of building any solar power plant, operating costs are extremely low compared to existing power technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] One approach to improving PV environmental performance is with circular PV modules that are designed to be easily disassembled.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Rooftop solar can be used locally, thus reducing transmission/distribution losses.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Compared to fossil and nuclear energy sources, very little research money has been invested in the development of solar cells, so there is considerable room for improvement.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Nevertheless, experimental high efficiency solar cells already have efficiencies of over 40% in case of concentrating photovoltaic cells and efficiencies are rapidly rising while mass-production costs are rapidly falling.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] In some states of the United States, much of the investment in a home-mounted system may be lost if the homeowner moves and the buyer puts less value on the system than the seller.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] The city of Berkeley developed an innovative financing method to remove this limitation, by adding a tax assessment that is transferred with the home to pay for the solar panels.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] Now known as PACE, Property Assessed Clean Energy, 30 U.S. states have duplicated this solution.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] For behind-the-meter rooftop photovoltaic systems, the energy flow becomes two-way.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] When there is more local generation than consumption, electricity is exported to the grid, allowing for net metering.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] However, electricity networks traditionally are not designed to deal with two-way energy transfer, which may introduce technical issues.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] An over-voltage issue may come out as the electricity flows from these PV households back to the network.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] There are solutions to manage the over-voltage issue, such as regulating PV inverter power factor, new voltage and energy control equipment at electricity distributor level, re-conductor the electricity wires, demand side management, etc.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] There are often limitations and costs related to these solutions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/photovoltaics-p02] High generation during the middle of the day reduces the net generation demand, but higher peak net demand as the sun goes down can require rapid ramping of utility generating stations, producing a load profile called the duck curve.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] A **rectenna** (***rect*ifying ant*enna***) is a special type of receiving antenna that is used for converting electromagnetic energy into direct current (DC) electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] They are used in wireless power transmission systems that transmit power by radio waves.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] A simple rectenna element consists of a dipole antenna with a diode connected across the dipole elements.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The diode rectifies the AC induced in the antenna by the microwaves, to produce DC power, which powers a load connected across the diode.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Schottky diodes are usually used because they have the lowest voltage drop and highest speed and therefore have the lowest power losses due to conduction and switching.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Large rectennas consist of arrays of many power receiving elements such as dipole antennas.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The invention of the rectenna in the 1960s made long distance wireless power transmission feasible.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The rectenna was invented in 1964 and patented in 1969 by US electrical engineer William C.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Brown, who demonstrated it with a model helicopter powered by microwaves transmitted from the ground, received by an attached rectenna.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Since the 1970s, one of the major motivations for rectenna research has been to develop a receiving antenna for proposed solar power satellites, which would harvest energy from sunlight in space with solar cells and beam it down to Earth as microwaves to huge rectenna arrays.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] A proposed military application is to power drone reconnaissance aircraft with microwaves beamed from the ground, allowing them to stay aloft for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] In recent years, interest has turned to using rectennas as power sources for small wireless microelectronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The largest current use of rectennas is in RFID tags, proximity cards and contactless smart cards, which contain an integrated circuit (IC) which is powered by a small rectenna element.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] When the device is brought near an electronic reader unit, radio waves from the reader are received by the rectenna, powering up the IC, which transmits its data back to the reader.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The simplest crystal radio receiver, employing an antenna and a demodulating diode (rectifier), is actually a rectenna, although it discards the DC component before sending the signal to the headphones.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] People living near strong radio transmitters would occasionally discover that with a long receiving antenna, they could get enough electric power to light a light bulb.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] However, this example uses only one antenna having a limited capture area.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] A rectenna array uses multiple antennas spread over a wide area to capture more energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Researchers are experimenting with the use of rectennas to power sensors in remote areas and distributed networks of sensors, especially for IoT applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] RF rectennas are used for several forms of wireless power transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] In the microwave range, experimental devices have reached a power conversion efficiency of 85–90%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The record conversion efficiency for a rectenna is 90.6% for 2.45 GHz, with lower efficiency of about 82% achieved at 5.82 GHz.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] In principle, similar devices, scaled down to the proportions used in nanotechnology, can be used to convert light directly into electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] This type of device is called an *optical rectenna* (or "nantenna").
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Theoretically, high efficiencies can be maintained as the device shrinks, but to date efficiency has been limited, and so far there has not been convincing evidence that rectification has been achieved at optical frequencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The University of Missouri previously reported on work to develop low-cost, high-efficiency optical-frequency rectennas.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Other prototype devices were investigated in a collaboration between the University of Connecticut and Penn State Altoona using a grant from the National Science Foundation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] With the use of atomic layer deposition it has been suggested that conversion efficiencies of solar energy to electricity higher than 70% could eventually be achieved.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Creating an ultra-fast diode capable of rectifying the high frequency oscillations, at frequency of c.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Below are a few examples of potential paths to creating diodes that would be fast enough to rectify optical and near-optical radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] A promising path towards creating these ultrafast diodes has been in the form of "geometric diodes".
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] Graphene geometric diodes have been reported to rectify terahertz radiation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] In April 2020, geometric diodes were reported in silicon nanowires.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/rectenna] The wires were shown experimentally to rectify up to 40 GHz, that result was the limit of the instrument used, and the wires theoretically may be able to rectify signals in the terahertz region as well.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A **thermoelectric generator** (**TEG**), also called a **Seebeck generator**, is a solid state device that converts heat (driven by temperature differences) directly into electrical energy through a phenomenon called the *Seebeck effect* (a form of thermoelectric effect).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators function like heat engines, but are less bulky and have no moving parts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] However, TEGs are typically more expensive and less efficient.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] When the same principle is used in reverse to create a heat gradient from an electric current, it is called a thermoelectric (or Peltier) cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators could be used in power plants and factories to convert waste heat into additional electrical power and in automobiles as automotive thermoelectric generators (ATGs) to increase fuel efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Radioisotope thermoelectric generators use radioisotopes to generate the required temperature difference to power space probes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators can also be used alongside solar panels.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In 1821, Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a thermal gradient formed between two different conductors can produce electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] At the heart of the thermoelectric effect is that a temperature gradient in a conducting material results in heat flow; this results in the diffusion of charge carriers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In 1834, Jean Charles Athanase Peltier discovered the reverse effect, that running an electric current through the junction of two dissimilar conductors could, depending on the direction of the current, cause it to act as a heater or cooler.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] George Cove had accidentally invented a photovoltaic panel, despite intending to invent a thermoelectric generator with thermocouples, in 1909.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] He notes that heat alone didn't produce any power, only incident light, but he had no explanation for how it could be working.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The operational principle is now understood to have been a very simple form of Schottky junction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The typical efficiency of TEGs is around 5–8%, although it can be higher.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Older devices used bimetallic junctions and were bulky.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] More recent devices use highly doped semiconductors made from bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3), lead telluride (PbTe), calcium manganese oxide (Ca2Mn3O8), or combinations thereof, depending on application temperature.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] These are solid-state devices and unlike dynamos have no moving parts, with the occasional exception of a fan or pump to improve heat transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] If the hot region is around 1273K and the ZT values of 3 - 4 are implemented, the efficiency is approximately 33-37%; allowing TEG's to compete with certain heat engine efficiencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric power generators consist of three major components: thermoelectric materials, thermoelectric modules and thermoelectric systems that interface with the heat source.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric materials generate power directly from the heat by converting temperature differences into electric voltage.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] These materials must have both high electrical conductivity (σ) and low thermal conductivity (κ) to be good thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Having low thermal conductivity ensures that when one side is made hot, the other side stays cold, which helps to generate a large voltage while in a temperature gradient.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The measure of the magnitude of electrons flow in response to a temperature difference across that material is given by the Seebeck coefficient (S).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The efficiency of a given material to produce a thermoelectric power is simply estimated by its "figure of merit" zT = S2σT/κ.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] For many years, the main three semiconductors known to have both low thermal conductivity and high power factor were bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3), lead telluride (PbTe), and silicon germanium (SiGe).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Some of these materials have somewhat rare elements which make them expensive.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Today, the thermal conductivity of semiconductors can be lowered without affecting their high electrical properties using nanotechnology.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] This can be achieved by creating nanoscale features such as particles, wires or interfaces in bulk semiconductor materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] However, the manufacturing processes of nano-materials are still challenging.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators are all-solid-state devices that do not require any fluids for fuel or cooling, making them non-orientation dependent allowing for use in zero-gravity or deep-sea applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The solid-state design allows for operation in severe environments.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators have no moving parts which produce a more reliable device that does not require maintenance for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The durability and environmental stability have made thermoelectrics a favorite for NASA's deep space explorers among other applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] One of the key advantages of thermoelectric generators outside of such specialized applications is that they can potentially be integrated into existing technologies to boost efficiency and reduce environmental impact by producing usable power from waste heat.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A thermoelectric module is a circuit containing thermoelectric materials which generate electricity from heat directly.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A thermoelectric module consists of two dissimilar thermoelectric materials joined at their ends: an n-type (with negative charge carriers), and a p-type (with positive charge carriers) semiconductor.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Direct electric current will flow in the circuit when there is a temperature difference between the ends of the materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] where $\sigma$ is the local conductivity, S is the Seebeck coefficient (also known as thermopower), a property of the local material, and $\nabla T$ is the temperature gradient.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In application, thermoelectric modules in power generation work in very tough mechanical and thermal conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Because they operate in a very high-temperature gradient, the modules are subject to large thermally induced stresses and strains for long periods.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] They also are subject to mechanical fatigue caused by a large number of thermal cycles.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thus, the junctions and materials must be selected so that they survive these tough mechanical and thermal conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Also, the module must be designed such that the two thermoelectric materials are thermally in parallel, but electrically in series.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The efficiency of a thermoelectric module is greatly affected by the geometry of its design.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators are made of several thermopiles, each consisting of many thermocouples made of a connected n-type and p-type material.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The arrangement of the thermocouples is typically in three main designs: planar, vertical, and mixed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Planar design involves thermocouples put onto a substrate horizontally between the heat source and cool side, resulting in the ability to create longer and thinner thermocouples, thereby increasing the thermal resistance and temperature gradient and eventually increasing voltage output.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Vertical design has thermocouples arranged vertically between the hot and cool plates, leading to high integration of thermocouples as well as a high output voltage, making this design the most widely used design commercially.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The mixed design has the thermocouples arranged laterally on the substrate while the heat flow is vertical between plates.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Microcavities under the hot contacts of the device allow for a temperature gradient, which allows for the substrate's thermal conductivity to affect the gradient and efficiency of the device.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] For microelectromechanical systems, TEGs can be designed on the scale of handheld devices to use body heat in the form of thin films.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Flexible TEGs for wearable electronics are able to be made with novel polymers through additive manufacturing or thermal spraying processes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Cylindrical TEGs for using heat from vehicle exhaust pipes can also be made using circular thermocouples arranged in a cylinder.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Many designs for TEGs can be made for the different devices they are applied to.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Using thermoelectric modules, a thermoelectric system generates power by taking in heat from a source such as a hot exhaust flue.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] To operate, the system needs a large temperature gradient, which is not easy in real-world applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The cold side must be cooled by air or water.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Heat exchangers are used on both sides of the modules to supply this heating and cooling.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] There are many challenges in designing a reliable TEG system that operates at high temperatures.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Achieving high efficiency in the system requires extensive engineering design to balance between the heat flow through the modules and maximizing the temperature gradient across them.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] To do this, designing heat exchanger technologies in the system is one of the most important aspects of TEG engineering.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In addition, the system requires to minimize the thermal losses due to the interfaces between materials at several places.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Another challenging constraint is avoiding large pressure drops between the heating and cooling sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] If AC power is required (such as for powering equipment designed to run from AC mains power), the DC power from the TE modules must be passed through an inverter, which lowers efficiency and adds to the cost and complexity of the system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Only a few known materials to date are identified as thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Most thermoelectric materials today have a zT, the figure of merit, value of around 1, such as in bismuth telluride (Bi2Te3) at room temperature and lead telluride (PbTe) at 500–700 K.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] However, in order to be competitive with other power generation systems, TEG materials should have a zT of 2–3.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Most research in thermoelectric materials has focused on increasing the Seebeck coefficient (S) and reducing the thermal conductivity, especially by manipulating the nanostructure of the thermoelectric materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Because both the thermal and electrical conductivity correlate with the charge carriers, new means must be introduced in order to conciliate the contradiction between high electrical conductivity and low thermal conductivity, as is needed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] When selecting materials for thermoelectric generation, a number of other factors need to be considered.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] During operation, ideally, the thermoelectric generator has a large temperature gradient across it.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermal expansion will then introduce stress in the device which may cause fracture of the thermoelectric legs or separation from the coupling material.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The mechanical properties of the materials must be considered and the coefficient of thermal expansion of the n and p-type material must be matched reasonably well.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In segmented thermoelectric generators, the material's compatibility must also be considered to avoid incompatibility of relative current, defined as the ratio of electrical current to diffusion heat current, between segment layers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] When the compatibility factor from one segment to the next differs by more than a factor of about two, the device will not operate efficiently.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The material parameters determining s (as well as zT) are temperature-dependent, so the compatibility factor may change from the hot side to the cold side of the device, even in one segment.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] This behavior is referred to as self-compatibility and may become important in devices designed for wide-temperature application.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Many TEG materials are employed in commercial applications today.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Highest temperatures material (up to 1300 K): materials fabricated from silicon-germanium (SiGe) alloys.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Although these materials still remain the cornerstone for commercial and practical applications in thermoelectric power generation, significant advances have been made in synthesizing new materials and fabricating material structures with improved thermoelectric performance.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Recent research has focused on improving the material's figure-of-merit (zT), and hence the conversion efficiency, by reducing the lattice thermal conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Researchers are trying to develop new thermoelectric materials for power generation by improving the figure-of-merit zT.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] One example of these materials is the semiconductor compound ß-Zn4Sb3, which possesses an exceptionally low thermal conductivity and exhibits a maximum zT of 1.3 at a temperature of 670K.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] This material is also relatively inexpensive and stable up to this temperature in a vacuum, and can be a good alternative in the temperature range between materials based on Bi2Te3 and PbTe.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Among the most exciting developments in thermoelectric materials was the development of single crystal tin selenide which produced a record zT of 2.6 in one direction.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Other new materials of interest include Skutterudites, Tetrahedrites, and rattling ions crystals.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Besides improving the figure-of-merit, there is increasing focus to develop new materials by increasing the electrical power output, decreasing cost and developing environmentally friendly materials.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] For example, when the fuel cost is low or almost free, such as in waste heat recovery, then the cost per watt is only determined by the power per unit area and the operating period.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] As a result, it has initiated a search for materials with high power output rather than conversion efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] For example, the rare earth compounds YbAl3 has a low figure-of-merit, but it has a power output of at least double that of any other material, and can operate over the temperature range of a waste heat source.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] To increase the figure of merit (zT), a material's thermal conductivity should be minimized while its electrical conductivity and Seebeck coefficient is maximized.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In most cases, methods to increase or decrease one property result in the same effect on other properties due to their interdependence.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A novel processing technique exploits the scattering of different phonon frequencies to selectively reduce lattice thermal conductivity without the typical negative effects on electrical conductivity from the simultaneous increased scattering of electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In a bismuth antimony tellurium ternary system, liquid-phase sintering is used to produce low-energy semicoherent grain boundaries, which do not have a significant scattering effect on electrons.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The breakthrough is then applying a pressure to the liquid in the sintering process, which creates a transient flow of the Te rich liquid and facilitates the formation of dislocations that greatly reduce the lattice conductivity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The ability to selectively decrease the lattice conductivity results in reported zT value of 1.86, which is a significant improvement over the current commercial thermoelectric generators with zT ~ 0.3–0.6.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] These improvements highlight the fact that in addition to the development of novel materials for thermoelectric applications, using different processing techniques to design microstructure is a viable and worthwhile effort.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] In fact, it often makes sense to work to optimize both composition and microstructure.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectric generators (TEG) have a variety of applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Frequently, thermoelectric generators are used for low power remote applications or where bulkier but more efficient heat engines such as Stirling engines would not be possible.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Unlike heat engines, the solid state electrical components typically used to perform thermal to electric energy conversion have no moving parts.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The thermal to electric energy conversion can be performed using components that require no maintenance, have inherently high reliability, and can be used to construct generators with long service-free lifetimes.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] This makes thermoelectric generators well suited for equipment with low to modest power needs in remote uninhabited or inaccessible locations such as mountaintops, the vacuum of space, or the deep ocean.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Solar cells use only the high-frequency part of the radiation, while the low-frequency heat energy is wasted.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Several patents about the use of thermoelectric devices in parallel or cascade configuration with solar cells have been filed.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The idea is to increase the efficiency of the combined solar/thermoelectric system to convert solar radiation into useful electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Conventional solar cells also suffer from decreased efficiency (-0.45%/°C) as temperature increases, and the inclusion of TEGs could help dissipate this waste heat while simultaneously increasing solar panel efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] There are two potential methods for coupling TEGs to photovoltaic panels.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Mechanically, the simplest is a thermally coupled system.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] This involves mounting TEGs in an array behind the PV panel.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Heat flows from the panel's rear surface into the hot side of the TE modules, which must be cooled on the other side.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A simple approach to generate the necessary temperature gradient across the TEGs is to apply heat sinks to promote convective cooling.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The second system is to optically couple photovoltaic cells with TEGs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Using mirrors and filters, incoming solar irradiance is split into two bands.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The higher-wavelength infrared spectrum is diverted to an array of TEGs where the thermal energy is scavenged for electricity generation.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] All other wavelengths are sent to the photovoltaic panel where it is converted to electricity.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Under ambient conditions, with thermally coupled systems, efficiencies of 3.05% were reported.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Higher gains have been noted under optimized conditions.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] One research group placed a PV-TEG system in an evacuated chamber to prevent convection on the top (hot) surface of the PV array, and to allow them to more carefully control the temperature gradient across the TEGs.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] They reported an efficiency increase of the TEGs from previously reported values of 0.5% up to 4.4%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Another method for regulating the temperature gradient across TEGs is the use of phase-change materials (PCMs).
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] These materials can help maintain a constant cold-side temperature over the entire panel area and avoid hot spots that may reduce PV efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] They also maintain the cold-side of the TEGs at a fixed temperature, and can help smooth out power generation and thus efficiency.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Organic-metal hybrid PCMs use nontoxic materials like coconut oil or beeswax coupled with metallic nanoparticles to facilitate thermal conduction into the material for efficient heat transfer.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] All of the practical limitations to implementation discussed above apply to these PV-TEG systems.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Until TEGs can produce higher than single-digit efficiencies under typical temperature gradients in ambient conditions, they will remain on the fringe of commercial development.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The added cost of including TEG arrays on solar panels cannot be justified for the marginal efficiency gains seen with current materials and architectures.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The Institute of Optics has announced a Solar Thermoelectric Generator (STEG) capable of efficiencies claimed to be up to 15%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] While TEG technology has been used in military and aerospace applications for decades, new TE materials and systems are being developed to generate power using low or high temperatures waste heat, and that could provide a significant opportunity in the near future.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] These systems can also be scalable to any size and have lower operation and maintenance cost.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] The global market for thermoelectric generators is estimated to be US$320 million in 2015 and US$472 million in 2021; up to US$1.44 billion by 2030 with a CAGR of 11.8%.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Today, North America captures 66% of the market share and it will continue to be the biggest market in the near future.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] However, Asia-Pacific and European countries are projected to grow at relatively higher rates.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Small scale thermoelectric generators are also in the early stages of investigation in wearable technologies to reduce or replace charging and boost charge duration.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Recent studies focused on the novel development of a flexible inorganic thermoelectric, silver selenide, on a nylon substrate.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Thermoelectrics represent particular synergy with wearables by harvesting energy directly from the human body creating a self-powered device.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] One project used n-type silver selenide on a nylon membrane.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Silver selenide is a narrow bandgap semiconductor with high electrical conductivity and low thermal conductivity, making it perfect for thermoelectric applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Low power TEG or "sub-watt" (i.e. generating up to 1 watt peak) market is a growing part of the TEG market, capitalizing on the latest technologies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] Main applications are sensors, low power applications and more globally Internet of things applications.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/thermoelectric-generator] A specialized market research company indicated that 100,000 units have been shipped in 2014 and expects 9 million units per year by 2020.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] A **vibration powered generator** is a type of electric generator that converts the kinetic energy from vibration into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The vibration may be from sound pressure waves or other ambient vibrations.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Vibration powered generators usually consist of a resonator which is used to amplify the vibration source, and a transducer mechanism which converts the energy from the vibrations into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The transducer usually consists of a magnet and coil or a piezoelectric crystal.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Electromagnetic based generators use Faraday's law of induction to convert the kinetic energy of the vibrations into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] They consist of magnets attached to a flexible membrane or cantilever beam and a coil.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The vibrations cause the distance between the magnet and coil to change, causing a change in magnetic flux and resulting in an electromagnetic force being produced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Generally, the coil is made using a diamagnetic material as these materials have weaker interactions with the magnet that would dampen the vibration.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The main advantage of this type of generator is that it is able to produce more power than the piezoelectric generators.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Electromagnetic based vibration-powered generators have been commercialized.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] A miniature electromagnetic vibration energy generator was developed by a team from the University of Southampton in 2007.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This particular device consists of a cantilever beam with a magnet attached to the end.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The beam moves up and down as the device is subjected to vibrations from surrounding sources.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This device allows sensors in hard-to-access locations to be powered without electrical wires or batteries that need to be replaced.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The generator was developed to be used in air compressors, and is able to power things in high vibration environments like sensors on machinery in manufacturing plants, or sensors that monitor the health of bridges.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] One of the major limitations of the magnetic vibration energy harvester developed at the University of Southampton is the size of the generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] At approximately one cubic centimeter, this device would be much too large to be used in modern electronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Future improvements on the size of the device could make it an ideal power source for medically implanted devices such as pacemakers.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] According to the team that created the device, the vibrations from the heart muscles would be enough to allow the generator to power a pacemaker.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This would eliminate the need to replace the batteries surgically.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] In 2012 a group at Northwestern University developed a vibration-powered generator out of polymer in the form of a spring.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This device was able to harvest the energy from vibrations at the same frequencies as the University of Southampton groups cantilever based device but at approximately one third the size of the other device.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Piezoelectric based generators use thin membranes or cantilever beams made of piezoelectric crystals as a transducer mechanism.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] When the crystal is put under strain by the kinetic energy of the vibration a small amount of current is produced thanks to the piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] These mechanisms are usually very simple with few moving parts, and they tend to have a very long service life.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This makes them the most popular method of harvesting the energy from vibrations.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] These mechanisms can be manufactured using the MEMS fabrication process, which allows them to be created on a very small scale.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The ability to make piezoelectric generators on such a small scale is the main advantage of this method over the electromagnetic generators, especially when the generator is being developed to power microelectronic devices.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Piezoelectric vibration generator has been commercialized.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] One piezoelectric generator being developed uses water droplets at the end of a piezoelectric cantilever beam.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The water droplets hang from the end of the beam and are subjected to excitation by the kinetic energy of the vibrations.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This results in the water droplet oscillating, which in turn causes the beam they are hanging from to deflect up and down.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This deflection is the strain which is converted to energy through the piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] A major advantage to this method is that it can be tailored towards a wide range of excitation frequencies.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The natural frequency of the water droplet is a function of its size; therefore changing the size of the water droplet allows for the matching of the natural frequency of the droplet and the frequency of the pressure wave being converted into electrical energy.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Matching these frequencies produces the largest amplitude oscillation of the water droplet, resulting in a large force and larger strain on the piezoelectric beam.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Another application seeks to use the vibrations created during flight in aircraft to power the electronics on the plane that currently rely on batteries.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] Such a system would allow for a reliable energy source, and reduce maintenance as batteries would no longer need to be replaced and piezoelectric systems have a long service life.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This system is used with a resonator, which allows the airflow to form a high amplitude steady tone.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] The same principle is used in many wind instruments, converting the airflow provided by the musician into a loud steady tone.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This tone is used as the vibration that is converted from kinetic to electric energy by the piezoelectric generator.
[src:energy-harvesting-deep/vibration-powered-generator] This application is still in the early stages of development; the concept has been proven on a scale model but the system still needs to be optimized before it is tested on a full scale.
